    <h2>FOI basics</h2>

    <section>
      <h3 id="what-is-recorded-information">What is recorded information?</h3>
      <p>FOI gives you the right to access <strong>recorded information</strong> that is held by <strong>public authorities</strong>.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Public authorities</strong> include government departments, local councils, hospitals, schools, universities, prisons and many more.</li>
        <li><strong>Recorded information</strong> is simply information that has been written down, printed or stored somewhere on a computer system. This includes data, documents, letters, reports, emails, minutes of meetings, maps, photographs, sound and video recordings and much more. If the information has been recorded, you can ask to see it.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">

      <h3 id="how-do-you-ask-for-it">How do you ask for it?</h3>
      <p>You can find more about the exact format a request needs to take later on, but the important thing to remember is that you don’t need to worry about using a special form of words or formal language.</p>
      <p>A short and simple note saying what information you want is absolutely fine. You can write an FOI request using the same language you would use when writing a note to a friend or family member.</p>

      <div class="card card-alert">
        <p class="card-header text-with-icon">
          <svg aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" width="16" height="24" viewBox="0 0 10 16" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
